WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.710 --> 00:00:03.340
&gt;&gt; Lola Pyne: Hello and welcome

00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:06.210
to our program honoring
young writers of the A Book

00:00:06.210 --> 00:00:08.980
That Shaped Me summer
writing contest.

00:00:08.980 --> 00:00:10.280
I'm Lola Pyne.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:12.270
And I work in the
Office of Communications

00:00:12.270 --> 00:00:14.150
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:14.150 --> 00:00:17.430
One of my favorite projects
here at the largest library

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:20.860
in the world is managing the
A Book That Shaped Me program

00:00:20.860 --> 00:00:23.910
which gives area young
people a unique opportunity

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:26.630
to participate in the
National Book Festival,

00:00:26.630 --> 00:00:30.330
which is the library's premier
outreach event celebrating books

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:31.770
and reading.

00:00:31.770 --> 00:00:34.720
We're delighted that today's
contest presentation will be

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:37.080
emceed by Eun Yang,
who is no stranger

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:39.510
to the National Book Festival.

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:42.300
[ Applause ]

00:00:42.300 --> 00:00:45.140
Eun is an Emmy Award
winning television anchor

00:00:45.140 --> 00:00:47.390
for NBC4 Washington.

00:00:47.390 --> 00:00:49.760
In addition in anchoring
News4 Today,

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:52.890
she files compelling
community stories about people

00:00:52.890 --> 00:00:56.220
and organizations important
to the Washington area

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:58.760
and has been an author
introducer for the book festival

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:01.400
for the past eight years.

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:04.230
She is also the mother of
three and a proponent of books

00:01:04.230 --> 00:01:06.090
and reading for young people.

00:01:06.090 --> 00:01:09.500
I'm pleased to turn the
program over to Eun.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:13.350
&gt;&gt; Eun Yang: Thank you Lola.

00:01:13.350 --> 00:01:15.840
Lola, thank you so much.

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:18.610
Good morning everyone
and welcome

00:01:18.610 --> 00:01:20.110
to the National Book Festival.

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:23.600
It is one of my favorite
events of the whole year.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:25.420
I clear my calendar
for this event.

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:27.380
I have three kids,
as Lola mentioned.

00:01:27.380 --> 00:01:28.680
Two of them are playing soccer.

00:01:28.680 --> 00:01:30.070
I brought one of them with me.

00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:31.480
And she's right.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:36.070
I am such a huge fan
of books and reading.

00:01:36.070 --> 00:01:38.380
Books take you on adventures.

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:40.110
They help you see the world

00:01:40.110 --> 00:01:41.630
through so many different
perspectives.

00:01:41.630 --> 00:01:44.980
You don't even have to
leave your house to go

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:48.360
and meet new people
and interesting things.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:51.320
And one of the best things
about books is they teach you

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:55.380
so much more about other
people and more about yourself,

00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:58.220
which is what this essay
contest is all about.

00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:01.130
I'm so serious about reading
and I'm such a mean mom that,

00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:03.370
of course, there's a
lot of reading to do

00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:05.100
at my house over the summer.

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:09.300
And, in fact, I made my
kids write a book report.

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:13.130
No, it was not required by the
school but I wanted to know

00:02:13.130 --> 00:02:15.200
that my kids not only
are reading the words,

00:02:15.200 --> 00:02:17.240
because they're all voracious
readers and they can eat

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:19.230
up the books, but that
they have an understanding

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:20.530
of what they're reading.

00:02:20.530 --> 00:02:22.680
So, sorry guys, it's what I do.

00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:24.900
It's because I love you and
it's because I love books

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:26.200
and I know you do too.

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:27.500
So welcome.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:28.800
It's going to be
such a great day.

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:31.920
Today, Lola and I are joined
on the stage by Jamie Uphold

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.810
from the Mensa Education
and Research Foundation,

00:02:34.810 --> 00:02:37.650
who also served as one
of the grand prize judges

00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:39.800
of this year's contest,
a big job I know.

00:02:39.800 --> 00:02:41.100
Very tough.

00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:42.530
So many good essays out there.

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:46.040
A Book That Shaped Me was
launched by the Library

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:49.380
of Congress in 2012 with the
DC Public Library and has

00:02:49.380 --> 00:02:52.090
since expanded through
the mid-Atlantic region.

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:57.280
The contest asks rising fifth
and sixth graders to reflect

00:02:57.280 --> 00:02:59.730
on a book that has
shaped their lives,

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:02.320
influencing the way
they see themselves,

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:04.550
their community, or their world.

00:03:04.550 --> 00:03:07.250
Students enter by
writing a one-page essay

00:03:07.250 --> 00:03:09.320
that then they submit in person

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:13.370
to a participating public
library in Washington DC,

00:03:13.370 --> 00:03:18.220
Maryland, Virginia, Delaware,
Pennsylvania, or West Virginia.

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:20.430
The essays are first
judged by members

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:23.970
of the American Association
of School Librarians,

00:03:23.970 --> 00:03:25.580
so these are very
important judges.

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:28.950
Then, the 30 finalists being
honored today were selected

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:31.930
by that panel that
represent these five states

00:03:31.930 --> 00:03:35.240
that received essays
over the summer.

